# Refactoring & Engineer Fundamentals

Code must be **short, clear, maintainable, and scalable**. These are baseline expectations.

## Core principles

- **DRY** – One place for each fact or behavior. Reuse or extract; no copy-paste. Derive types from data (e.g. from a registry) instead of hand-written parallel lists.
- **KISS** – Simplest solution that works. No speculative abstraction; no cleverness for its own sake.
- **YAGNI** – Implement what’s needed now. No “we might need this later” code.
- **Single Responsibility** – One function/type/module, one clear purpose. If you need “and” to describe it, split it.
- **Single source of truth** – One registry, one config, one mapping. Everything else derives from it. Adding a new case = one change in one place.
- **No linter/test ignores** – Fix the cause or adjust config for the whole project. Per-line ignores hide debt.
- **New automation** – Mise task only; logic in the task body. No new scripts in `tools/` or elsewhere. See `.cursor/rules/mise-tasks.mdc`.

## Naming & clarity

- Names reveal intent. `getUserById` not `getData`. `isValid` not `check`.
- No magic numbers or strings. Use named constants or config. Exceptions: 0, 1, -1 in obvious contexts.
- Comments explain **why**, not what. If the code needs a comment to say what it does, simplify the code.

## Functions

- Small: do one thing, fit on one screen. Compose small functions instead of big branching ones.
- Pure when possible: same inputs → same outputs, no hidden state or side effects. Push I/O to the edges.
- Few parameters (≤3). Use an options object for more. No boolean flags that change behavior in opaque ways.
- Return early; avoid deep nesting. Guard clauses over `if/else` chains when it helps readability.

## Types & APIs

- Prefer one generic signature over many overloads when the type system can infer (e.g. from a literal first argument).
- Types derive from runtime data: `type X = { [K in keyof registry]: ... }`. No duplicate type list that mirrors a registry.
- Public API: minimal surface. Internal helpers stay non-exported unless needed elsewhere.

## Errors & boundaries

- Fail fast: validate at boundaries, return errors or throw clearly. No silent swallow (empty catch, ignore return).
- Errors are values when the language allows (e.g. Result/Either). One consistent style per codebase.
- No generic `catch (e)` without handling or rethrowing with context.

## Dependencies & config

- Explicit over implicit: pass config and dependencies in; no global state or hidden imports for behavior.
- Dependencies point inward: domain/core does not depend on shell, UI, or I/O. See `assets/docs/guides/FCIS.guide.md`.

## Scalable registries / factories

- One map/object defines the set. Types and functions derive from it. No parallel overload list.
- Adding an item = (1) add to the registry, (2) implement the item. No new overloads, no new switch arms, no edits in multiple files.
- One generic signature per function when inference from the first argument is enough.

## Before writing

- Can an existing function/type be reused?
- Can a generic or shared helper replace duplication?
- Are N overloads necessary, or can one signature + inference suffice?

## After writing

- Would a peer understand this in 30 seconds?
- Is this the shortest clear version?
- Any linter/test ignores? Remove or fix the cause.
- If we add another X (factory, handler, etc.), do we touch only one place?

## Prompts that raise the bar

- *"Implement to production standard: DRY, single source of truth, scalable. No ignores. Follow refactoring rules."*
- *"Propose the minimal type-safe API first. One signature per function if inference allows."*
- *"Adding a new X must require only [one place]. No parallel overloads or duplicate mappings."*
- *"Review for: duplicate overloads, or edits in more than one place when we add a new X."*
